Historical overview
Origins at Harvard (2003-2004)
Before Facebook, Mark Zuckerberg built Facemash at Harvard. On February 4, 2004, he launched
TheFacebook as a Harvard-only network. The service quickly expanded beyond Harvard to other universities,
while the company incorporated in Delaware on July 29, 2004 as TheFacebook, Inc.[2][5]
From campus network to Facebook (2005-2006)
In 2005 the company shifted from TheFacebook to Facebook, Inc., and the public-facing service dropped the
leading "The" after the acquisition of facebook.com in August 2005. By 2006, Facebook had moved from a
campus-focused network toward a broader service open to anyone age 13 or older with a valid email

Page 2
address.[3][5][6]
Platform era and rapid expansion (2007-2011)
Facebook''s growth accelerated through features such as the News Feed and the broader Facebook Platform.
During this period the company became one of the defining social networks of the web and expanded
globally, moving from a student identity product to a mass-market communications and advertising
platform.[5][6]
Public company and ecosystem growth (2012-2020)
Facebook, Inc. completed its IPO in May 2012 and continued broadening its product ecosystem, including
Messenger, Instagram, and WhatsApp as part of the wider company portfolio. By the late 2010s the company
was operating as a large multi-product technology business rather than a single-site social network.[4][7]
Meta era (2021-present)
On October 28, 2021, the company announced that Facebook, Inc. would become Meta Platforms, Inc. The
rebrand signaled a corporate strategy centered on the metaverse and a broader family of apps and
technologies. Importantly, Facebook remained the name of the social networking service, while Meta became
the parent-company identity.[1][4]
Why the naming matters
When people say "Facebook," they may mean either the social network or the corporation behind it.
Historically, those are not always the same thing. From 2004 to 2005, the service launched as TheFacebook
and the corporation was TheFacebook, Inc. From May 11, 2005 until October 28, 2021, the corporation was
Facebook, Inc. Since October 28, 2021, the corporation has been Meta Platforms, Inc., while the consumer
service continues to be Facebook.[1][2][3][4][5]
